# Grey Gables Farm — design rules

## Aim for

- **Editorial / magazine** layout: typography and whitespace carry the design
- **Photography-forward**: real farm images are the hero; UI stays quiet
- **Restrained palette**: cream, parchment, sage, bark, stone — no accent rainbows
- **Flat surfaces**: hairline borders (`border-parchment`), no drop shadows unless essential
- **Tight radii**: `rounded-sm` (2px) at most; square image crops are fine
- **Calm motion**: color/underline on hover only — no scale, parallax, or entrance animations
- **Farm-forward, not themed**: no burlap, distressed wood, wheat icons, or “farm chic” clip art

## Avoid

- Generic Tailwind SaaS aesthetics (purple gradients, Inter-only, card grids everywhere)
- Oversized rounded cards (`rounded-xl`, `rounded-2xl`, `rounded-3xl`)
- Loud or multi-stop gradients (hero scrims should be a single flat overlay if needed)
- Glassmorphism (`backdrop-blur`, frosted `bg-white/60` headers)
- Startup UI patterns (pill buttons, floating action cards, “feature grids” with icons)
- Dashboard feel (dense stats, sidebars, widget cards)
- Trendy animation overload (`animate-pulse`, hover scale, staggered reveals)
- Rustic cliché textures (linen backgrounds, SVG grain, rope borders)
- Fake luxury gold accents or metallic gradients

## Component conventions

| Element | Use |
|--------|-----|
| Buttons | `rounded-sm`, sentence case, border or solid fill — not `rounded-full` pills |
| Cards / CTAs | Border + padding, no `shadow-sm` / `shadow-lg` |
| Images | Sharp or `rounded-sm` crop; captions below the image, not gradient overlays |
| Hero | Full-bleed photo + **flat** `bg-bark/40` overlay if text sits on image; prefer split layouts when possible |
| Header | Solid `bg-cream` or `bg-white`, no blur |
| Status chips | Small rectangular labels (`rounded-sm`), not pills |
| Spacing | Generous section padding; max width `max-w-6xl` |

## Tokens

Use shared classes from `app/globals.css`: `.btn`, `.card`, `.input`, `.chip`, `.image-frame`.

When adding UI, check existing components (`Button`, `Section`, `Hero`) before inventing new patterns.
